06693nam a22008535i 9780226363660DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20172016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016006708  a9780226363660  a(DE-B1597)522670  a(OCoLC)1005018049  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aP281b.M65 2016 4aP281 7aLAN0000002bisacsh04a41500aMood, Aspect, Modality Revisited :bNew Answers to Old Questions /ced. by Joanna Blaszczak, Krzysztof Migdalski, Dorota Klimek-Jankowska, Anastasia Giannakidou. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b17 halftones, 15 line drawings, 14 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart I. Tense, Aspect, and Modals: Their Categorial Status and Cross- linguistic Variation -- tChapter One. TAM Coding and Temporal Interpretation in West African Languages -- tChapter Two. Modals: Meaning Categories? -- tChapter 3. Epistemic Future and Epistemic MUST: Nonveridicality, Evidence, and Partial Knowledge -- tPart II. Irrealis Moods: Subjunctive and Imperative -- tChapter 4. On Finiteness and the Left Periphery: Focusing on Subjunctive -- tChapter 5. Evaluative Subjunctive and Nonveridicality -- tChapter 6. The Essence of a Category: Lessons from the Subjunctive -- tChapter 7. Imperatives as (Non-)modals -- tChapter 8. Approaching the Morphosyntax and Semantics of Mood -- tPart III. Aspectual Recursion and Aspectual Coercion -- tChapter 9. Aspectual Composition and Recursion -- tChapter 10. Can Semantic Theories Be Tested Experimentally? The Case of Aspectual Coercion -- tChapter 11. Aspectual Coercion versus Blocking: Experimental Evidence from an ERP Study of Polish Converbs -- tAbout the Editors -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past several decades, linguistic theorizing of tense, aspect, and mood (TAM), along with a strongly growing body of crosslinguistic studies, has revealed complexity in the data that challenges traditional distinctions and treatments of these categories. Mood, Aspect, Modality Revisited argues that it’s time to revisit our conventional assumptions and reconsider our foundational questions: What exactly is a linguistic category? What kinds of categories do labels such as “subjunctive,” “imperative,” “future,” and “modality” truly refer to? In short, how categorical are categories? Current literature assumes a straightforward link between grammatical category and semantic function, and descriptions of well-studied languages have cultivated a sense of predictability in patterns over time. As the editors and contributors of Mood, Aspect, Modality Revisited prove, however, this predictability and stability vanish in the study of lesser-known patterns and languages. The ten provocative essays gathered here present fascinating cutting-edge research demonstrating that the traditional grammatical distinctions are ultimately fluid—and perhaps even illusory. Developing groundbreaking and highly original theories, the contributors in this volume seek to unravel more general, fundamental principles of TAM that can help us better understand the nature of linguistic representations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxAspect. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxMood. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxTense. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  aTAM.  aaspect.  aaspectual markers.  agrammatical categories.  airrealis moods.  alinguistic categories.  amodality.  amood.  atense.1 aAmbar, Manuela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlaszczak, Joa